  {
    "page": 7,
    "block_id": "p10_v1scan_discovering_1_day_vulnerabilities_2023:block:007:017",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "Function and structure vulnerability detection. V1SCAN\nthen detects the vulnerabilities propagated to the target pro-\ngram. To respond flexibly to code changes unrelated to a\nvulnerability, V1SCAN focuses on the core code lines that\nwere added or deleted in the security patch [34,37].\nThe process of detecting vulnerabilities in functions and\nstructures comprises two steps.",
    "bbox": [
      53.64,
      230.59,
      295.77,
      314.68
    ],
    "reading_order": 17,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "partial"
  },
  {
    "page": 7,
    "block_id": "p10_v1scan_discovering_1_day_vulnerabilities_2023:block:007:018",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "S1. Hash comparison: First, V1SCAN compares the hash\nvalues of all functions (structures) in vulnerability sig-\nnatures with those of the target program. If a hash value\nthat belongs to both the signature and target program is\ndetected, V1SCAN determines that the vulnerability has\nbeen propagated to the target program. Otherwise, if a\nsimilar hash value is discovered, V1SCAN moves to the\nnext step, namely, line comparison.",
    "bbox": [
      55.93,
      319.73,
      295.77,
      415.78
    ],
    "reading_order": 18,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "partial"
  },
  {
    "page": 7,
    "block_id": "p10_v1scan_discovering_1_day_vulnerabilities_2023:block:007:019",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "S2. Line comparison: When a similar function (structure)\nis detected between the vulnerability signature and the\ntarget program, V1SCAN checks whether code deleted\nfrom (resp. added to) the patch was included (resp. was\nnot included) in the function (structure) of the target\nprogram. If this is satisfied, V1SCAN determines that\nthe target program contains the vulnerability.",
    "bbox": [
      55.93,
      418.06,
      294.79,
      502.15
    ],
    "reading_order": 19,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "partial"
  },
  {
    "page": 7,
    "block_id": "p10_v1scan_discovering_1_day_vulnerabilities_2023:block:007:020",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "Here, if we only consider the code syntax in the line com-\nparison, as with certain existing approaches (e.g., [35,37]),\nfalse positives or negatives may arise especially when the code\nmodified in the patch is short and general. Assume that the\ncode line “else” is added by the patch. This code line may\nexist in the vulnerable function. Hence, even if the vulnerable\nfunction is not patched, the function may be misinterpreted to\nbe safe because it contains the code line added by the patch.\nTherefore, we decided to consider the number of times\ndeleted (added) code lines appear in the target function. Sup-\npose that a security patch deletes the code line ldel and adds\nthe code line ladd to the function fv. Let the function after\napplying the patch be fp. V1SCAN counts the number of\ntimes ldel and ladd appear in fv and fp, respectively. There-\nafter, when a function f ′\nv similar to fv is detected through\nhash comparison, V1SCAN counts the number of times ldel\nand ladd appear in f ′\nv. If the result is the same as that of fv but\ndiffers from that of fp, f ′\nv is considered a vulnerable function.",
    "bbox": [
      54.0,
      507.56,
      295.82,
      727.08
    ],
    "reading_order": 20,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "partial"
  },
