  {
    "page": 7,
    "block_id": "p10_v1scan_discovering_1_day_vulnerabilities_2023:block:007:037",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "This method can distinguish between vulnerable and\npatched functions even when both deleted and added code\nlines exist in the target function. Therefore, V1SCAN can de-\ntect vulnerabilities with fewer false positives than existing\nsimple code syntax checking approaches.\nV1SCAN can detect exactly reused vulnerable functions\n(structures) with the aid of hash comparison and identify vul-\nnerable functions (structures) whose code syntax has been\nchanged using line comparison. This guarantees a higher\nvulnerability detection rate than the existing code-based ap-\nproach that considers only hash comparison (e.g., [14]) and\nlowers the false positive rate compared with the existing ap-\nproach that only considers line comparison (e.g., [12]).",
    "bbox": [
      317.55,
      232.16,
      559.66,
      387.63
    ],
    "reading_order": 37,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "partial"
  },
  {
    "page": 7,
    "block_id": "p10_v1scan_discovering_1_day_vulnerabilities_2023:block:007:038",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "Macro and variable vulnerability detection. To detect\nvulnerabilities in macros and variables (global and class\nvariables), V1SCAN compares the lines of code containing\nmacros and variables in vulnerability signatures to those in the\ntarget program. If all the lines of code containing macros (vari-\nables) deleted (resp. added) by the patch were included (resp.\nnot included) in the target program, V1SCAN determines that\nthe target program contains the vulnerability.\nIf the security patch did not add any lines of code, then only\nthe deleted lines of code are used to check for vulnerability\npropagation. On the other hand, if the patch did not delete\nany lines of code, it would be premature to conclude that the\nvulnerability was propagated by solely relying on the fact that\nthe lines of code added by the patch do not exist in the target\nprogram. Thus, V1SCAN omits the latter case to reduce false\nalarms. This could yield a small number of false negatives;\nhowever, this decision was made because the addition of lines\nof code containing a macro or variables by a security patch\nwithout removing any lines of code from all four vulnerable\ncode locations rarely occurs.",
    "bbox": [
      317.52,
      393.32,
      559.74,
      632.83
    ],
    "reading_order": 38,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "partial"
  },
  {
    "page": 7,
    "block_id": "p10_v1scan_discovering_1_day_vulnerabilities_2023:block:007:039",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "The vulnerability detection result of the improved code-\nbased approach in which false negatives are covered is ob-\ntained as the output of this phase. Among the vulnerabilities\nheld by the version-based approach (e.g., existing outside the\nfunction), the vulnerabilities detected in the code-based ap-\nproach are included in the detection result as correct answers,\nand all others are considered false positives and filtered out.",
    "bbox": [
      317.88,
      638.88,
      559.66,
      722.62
    ],
    "reading_order": 39,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "partial"
